To analyze the NYC taxi dataset, it is necessary to first define what constitutes a “real trip” and identify inconsistencies in the raw data.

1. Definition of a Real Trip

A trip is considered valid if it satisfies the following conditions:

Pickup and drop-off timestamps are present and logically ordered (pickup < drop-off)
Trip distance > 0
Fare amount ≥ 0
Passenger count ≥ 1
Pickup and drop-off locations are valid and not missing
2. Identification of Inconsistencies

The dataset may contain:

Trips with zero or negative distance
Negative or high fare values
Missing timestamps or locations
Drop-off time earlier than pickup time
Duplicate records
Unrealistic trip durations (too short or excessively long)
3. Data Cleaning Approach

To ensure data quality:

Remove records with missing critical fields (time, location, fare)
Filter out trips with invalid values (negative distance/fare)
Remove duplicates
Correct or discard inconsistent timestamp entries
Apply thresholds to eliminate outliers (extreme duration or fare)
4. Impact of Definition on Analysis

The definition of a “real trip” directly affects conclusions:

A strict definition improves accuracy but reduces dataset size
A lenient definition increases data volume but may introduce noise
Different definitions can lead to different interpretations of demand, revenue, and system efficiency
Conclusion

A “real trip” is defined based on logical consistency, valid values, and completeness of key attributes.
Establishing this definition ensures reliable analysis and prevents misleading conclusions about the taxi ecosystem.

